social_posts.post_text: Happy fungi Friday! Some of my adorable fungal isolates 😊🧫🎉 #bioremediation
Happy micro Monday! It finally snowed here! 😄❄️ Inspired me to post this awesome snowman ⛄️ plate created by @sarah.casey.richards using microbes isolated from plants 🌱💕
Happy Friday! One more festive plate for the season 🎄Created by @sarah.casey.richards with microbes (yeast, bacteria, algae) isolated from plants 🌱💕 Happy holidays to all! 🎉

Happy Tuesday! That time I took one of my Aspergillus images, did some color editing and made my own fabric 💕🎉🔬I miss making fabric. I need to come up with a new design so I can wear more of my favorite microbes 😂 #microbefashion

Happy Friday! An endophytic eukaryotic algal strain I isolated while working at Indigo Ag 🧫💚 It was used in the creation of various agar art plates I’ve posted- The Christmas tree plate, corn plate, and 3 floral themed plates. Such a beautiful color! In this image it’s growing on 50% PDA. Even though it’s not a fungus I still love it 😉🎉

Happy wee floof Wednesday! One of the cutest Aspergillus colonies I’ve encountered 😊 It’s an endophytic (lives in plant tissue 🌱) Aspergillus strain that I isolated a few years ago. The image was captured through a stereo microscope with my iPhone 🔬📱 I’m just so obsessed with those wee pom poms! 💕
So. Many. Fungi. 😻😻😻
Happy Wednesday! Love this cat + ❤️ created by @brimyselfandi for Valentine’s Day 😻🧫🎉 So cute!! #MadeWithMicrobes

Happy fungi Friday! 

#fungi #microbiology #sciart

Happy fungi Friday and Happy St Patrick’s Day! This festive Trichoderma strain felt perfect for today 🧫☘️ It was isolated from mine tailings and will be screened for bioremediation capabilities 🎉💕 Excited to see how it performs!

Happy fungi Friday! A shot of Penicillium vulpinum synnemata (singular- synnema) taken through a stereo microscope with my iPhone. Synnemata are asexual reproductive structures that are made up of compact conidiophores. So instead of each reproductive structure consisting of one conidiophore, like many fungi produce (see my Aspergillus images for an example of individual conidiophores), each of these spore bearing structures is made up of many conidiophores all squished or fused together (It’s why they’re so thick). Also, the green/blue heads are where the spores (conidia) are produced (the color is from the spores!). So. Many. Spores. I love this crazy fungus so much 😊💕 ALSO, in case anyone was curious- Penicillium vulpinum can be found in the wild growing on poo in the woods 👀

Happy tiny tufts Tuesday! Snapshots of soil and plant dilution plates. Love getting to actually see some of the fungi that are natural community members of soil and plant tissue! I know there are so many more that I haven’t seen and won’t get to see because they’re difficult to isolate, won’t grow without their host or without the presence of other microbes, etc. So many mystery microbes waiting to be discovered! Also, I love looking at soil and plants and thinking about all of the micro fungi present and how they interact with their community and host and how much we still don’t know. So crazy! And beautiful 😊🧫💕

Happy wee crystal Wednesday! I prepared citric acid slides for the first time yesterday and checked them out under the polarized scope this morning 🌈🔬Love how feathery the crystals appear in this section. I’ve seen many images of citric acid crystals before, but it was awesome seeing them with my own eyes, through my own scope, and finding compositions that I enjoy. I will be mounting my Nikon on the scope for high res images once the adapter arrives. Right now I’m just capturing images with my iPhone.
I prepared the slides by placing citric acid on a slide, flaming the bottom of the slide until the citric acid melted, and then let the slide sit overnight. This image was taken at 400x total magnification. My plan is to try preparing vitamin C slides next and then start exploring biological samples 😄 Also, fun fact- Aspergillus niger is used for the industrial production of citric acid!

Happy Friday! Vitamin C under a polarized light microscope with full wave plate 🌈🔬 Love the textures! 💕 I still have a few more citric acid and vitamin C images I’d like to post. I know they’re not microbes, but I enjoy them 😊 I promise I’ll get back to microbes soon!
Happy micro Monday! One more shot of citric acid crystals under polarized light 🔬🌈 Love the dimensions! I’ll post one more shot of vitamin C on Wednesday. Having a great time exploring these slides!
Happy wee Wednesday! Last vitamin C shot under polarized light 🔬 Love the colors and textures! Next post will be microbes 🧫
Happy myco Monday! A soil dilution plate full of Aspergillus flavus (the bright green/yellow colonies) 🧫 Media = dichloran rose bengal (DRB). Such a beautiful plate! 💕
Happy micro Monday! Beta alanine (amino acid) under polarized light 🔬 I love this composition 💕 So beautiful!

Happy Friday! Another image of beta alanine (amino acid) under polarized light 🔬💕 I really enjoyed this composition as well. It’s too wide for the entire image to fit, but I think the cropped version still does a good job of representing it. I stitched between 15-20 pics together to create this one. Such beautiful crystal formations! 🤩

Happy wee floof Wednesday! Aspergillus parasiticus stained with lactophenol cotton blue 💙 One of the cutest peanut and corn pathogens in my opinion 🥜🌽

Happy tiny tufts Tuesday! Working on new Microbes & Molecules designs. This is part of a design for Aspergillus niger & citric acid. The color in this image is a microscopic shot of citric acid that I captured through my polarized scope. Aspergillus niger is used for the industrial production of citric acid. What items do you use or consume that contain citric acid? It’s used in food, drinks, cleaning agents, cosmetics, and more! Check out what items you have that contain citric acid and next time you eat or use those items think of this wee fungus 💕
Happy wee floof Wednesday! Soil fungi isolated on Dichloran Rose Bengal agar 🧫💕

Happy myco Monday! Fungal pigment production after 4 weeks of growth 🧫❤️ Media = PDA. This was during the process of isolating environmental microbes. Pigment production was not the goal, just a fun by-product 😊 Love following all of the current research being conducted on fungal (and bacterial) pigments for sustainable textile and food dyes. So cool! Fungi produce so many interesting metabolites. Wish I had time to study them all 🧐

Happy streak plate Saturday! That time I tried to streak the Mario 1UP mushroom using 3 different Aspergillus strains: Green = A. flavus, Black = A. niger, Cream = A. terreus 🧫🍄 The growth was a little out of control 😂 but I had fun trying!

Happy wee floof Wednesday! Aspergillus oryzae 💙 This fungus, also known as koji, is used in the production of various fermented foods, such as soy sauce, miso, and sake. I love this adorable, beneficial fungus and the foods it helps to produce! 😄💕 What are your favorite microbes used in food production?

Happy tiny tufts Tuesday! Botrytis cinerea stained with lactophenol cotton blue 💙 Not only is this adorable fungus my favorite strawberry pathogen 🍓, it’s also know as Noble Rot 👑 in the wine industry and is used to produce sweet wines with unique flavor profiles (botrytized wines)🍷💕
Happy streak plate Saturday! That time I tried to streak Pusheen with Aspergillus niger 🧫😂🖤 #caturday

Happy Wednesday! Aspergillus flavus on CZA 💚 We often think of A. flavus as just a pathogen that produces aflatoxin. But the truth is that some A. flavus strains do not possess the gene cluster to produce aflatoxin and are non-toxigenic. In fact, the biocontrol AF36, which is used in agriculture to manage aflatoxin contamination, is an A. flavus strain! The non-toxigenic (or atoxigenic) strain is used to outcompete the toxigenic strains. Flavus vs flavus! Fungi, and microbes in general, are so interesting… Many of them are also really cute 😊 Like this A. flavus colony ✨
Happy tiny tufts Tuesday! Aspergillus nidulans stained with lactophenol cotton blue 💙

Happy Tuesday! Curvularia isolated from plant tissue 🌱 Love those spores 😊💕 The genus Curvularia contains various species that are plant pathogens as well as species that have been shown to impart benefits to plants (like improving plant growth!). Like us, plants have complex relationships with microbes 🧫🔬

Happy myco Monday! Because I love Penicillium vulpinum 😊💕 Look at those synnemata! Synnemata (singular: synnema) are asexual reproductive structures. They produce spores (the spores are the blue/green color!). Such a cool morphology! ✨
Happy tiny tufts Tuesday! Arthrobotrys robusta stained with rose bengal 💕 Love this nematophagous fungus (it can trap and digest nematodes)! Such a beautiful morphology 🌸

Happy fungi Friday! Remember the Penicillium vulpinum plate I posted recently? Well, these are P. vulpinum synnemata up close! 💕 I captured the image using my stereo scope and iPhone 🧫🔬 I love those wee spore bearing structures so much 😊 They’re so cool!
Happy Thursday! Aspergillus stained with lactophenol cotton blue 💙🔬 Isolated from plant tissue 🌱💕
Happy Thursday! Coprinopsis lagopus growing in mulch 💕 Also, I love slugs and snails, so this scene made me extra happy 😊🎉

Happy fungi Friday! Arthrobotrys robusta 💙 Love this nematode-trapping fungus 🪱 Many of the species in the genus Arthrobotrys are predators of nematodes and a number of them are currently being studied for their use in agriculture to protect plants from parasitic nematodes! 🌱🎉 So cool!

Happy fungi Friday! Penicillium nalgiovense isolated from salami 💕 This fungus is used in the production of dry-cured meats to help prevent harmful microbes from colonizing and spoiling the meat! 🎉 It, and other Penicillium species, also impact the characteristics and taste of salami. ALSO, it’s super cute 😊 Love this #fungalfriend
Happy Thursday! Fungi isolated from soil on Dichloran Rose Bengal agar 🧫 Love this composition 💕
Happy Halloween! 💀🍬🎉 This festive plate was created by @sayyrah_hope with bacteria isolated from plant tissue 🌱 I love it! So cute 💕
Happy fungi Friday! Fungi isolated from agricultural soil on DRB agar 🧫 The yellow-green colonies are Aspergillus flavus 💚 Adorable 😊 Also potentially toxigenic 👀

Happy wee Wednesday! Aspergillus clavatus isolated from soil 💕 Image captured through a stereo microscope with my iPhone 🤳 This colony will eventually turn blue-green as spores form and mature on these beautiful conidiophores 💙💚
Happy fungi Friday! Saccharomyces cerevisiae (commonly known as brewer’s yeast & baker’s yeast) 🤍 Fun fact: S. cerevisiae is Oregon’s official state microbe! 🎉 Love this fermentation friend 😊

Happy micro Monday! An Aspergillus terreus medusa head! 🔬Typically a conidiophore (specialized hypha, structure that looks like a stem) will give rise to a head, which then gives rise to phialides (or metulae + phialides, finger-like structures). The phialides then produce conidia (spores). In this image you can see that instead of producing phialides the head produced new conidiophores! So instead of one head, it has many heads! (I will share a labeled pic in my story) 🎉 Medusa heads are thought to be part of microcycle conidiation, which is when a fungus is stressed out by unfavorable environmental conditions and bypasses the normal lifecycle. We’re still learning about how and why they form though. 🧐 This sample was stained with lactophenol cotton blue 💙 and isolated from soil 🧫 So cute!
Arthrobotrys robusta edit 💗🌸 Love those adorable spores! Such a beautiful fungus 😊
Happy Holidays! Love this festive plate created by @sarah.casey.richards using bacteria, yeast, and eukaryotic algae isolated from plant tissue 🎄🧫🎉

Happy tiny tufts Tuesday! Immature Aspergillus flavus conidiophores 💕 The metulae and phialides have formed, and soon each phialide will generate a chain of conidia (spores)! This slide was prepared without stain 🔬 The sample was isolated from agricultural soil 🧫 Such a beautiful fungus!
Happy fungi Friday! Aspergillus stained with lactophenol cotton blue 💙🔬 Isolated from agricultural soil 🧫
